subSubSection.paragraph:
Diagnosis.

Lithocharodes fuscipennis

differs from its congeners by the specific color of the elytra, which are dark brown to black with the apical quarter conspicuously lighter, except on the elytral suture. It can be recognized also by the dispersed and fine punctures on the head and pronotum (
Fig. 1
); male tergite VIII with posterior margin slightly emarginated medially (
Fig. 11
), truncate in the female (
Fig. 14
); and male sternite VIII with posterior margin broadly rounded to truncate (
Fig. 12
), rounded in female (
Fig. 15
).

Male. Head:
Rectangular, 1.5 times longer than wide, basal half slightly wider; eyes somewhat prominent, 0.4 times length of temples; neck 1/3 basal width of head (
Fig. 1
). Antennae short, not reaching middle of pronotum; dense pubescence on antennomeres 5–11, increasing towards apex; scape, pedicel, and antennomere 3 somewhat conical; scape longest, as long as five subsequent antennomeres combined; pedicel and antennomere 3 subequal in length; antennomeres 4–10 transverse, increasing in width toward apex; antennomere 11 slightly longer than wide, as long as 2 preceding antennomeres combined (
Fig. 2
). Labrum convex and short, anterior margin deeply emarginated, with long setae (
Fig. 3
). Mandibles short and robust; internal margin asymmetrical, right mandible with 3 teeth, left mandible with 2 teeth; both with deep lateral groove (
Fig. 5
). Maxilla with galea shorter than lacinia; maxillary palpus with palpomere 1 shorter, as long as wide; palpomere 2 slightly longer than wide; palpomere 3 longest, 1.7 times longer than wide; palpomere 4 pointed, 0.8 times length of palpomere 3, 0.6 times apical width of palpomere 3 (
Fig. 4
). Labium with mentum very short and transverse, 3.5 times wider than long; labial palpomere 1 shortest, 0.7 times length of palpomere 2; palpomere 2 longest; palpomere 3 0.5 times width of palpomere 2 (
Fig. 6
). Gular sutures contiguous. 
Thorax:
Pronotum rectangular, 1.5 times longer than greatest width; apical 3/4 wider; angles rounded; superior line of hypomera very fine, fading out at 2/3–5/6 posteriorly, slightly deflected to ventral surface at level of procoxa and not joining inferior line. Elytra 2.0 times longer than wide; slightly shorter than pronotum (
Fig. 1
). Hind wings well-developed. Tibia with apical ctenidium, protibia with additional 4 subapical ctenidia (
Fig. 7
), meso- and metatibiae with additional 2 subapical ctenidia, basalmost reduced (
Figs. 8–9
). Tarsus simple, not dilated, tarsomere 5 longest, as long as 2 preceding tarsomeres combined; protarsomeres 1–4 more robust compared to meso- and metatarsomeres 1–4 and decreasing slightly in length to apex; mesotarsomere 1 2 times longer than mesotarsomere 2, mesotarsomeres 2–4 decreasing slightly in length to apex; metatarsomeres 1–4 decreasing slightly in length to apex. Tarsal formula 5-5-5. 
Abdomen:
Segments III–VI transverse, gradually widening to apex (
Fig. 1
); tergite VII subquadrate; sternite VII transverse; tergite VIII longer than wide, posterior margin slightly emarginated medially (
Fig. 11
); sternite VIII longer than wide, posterior margin broadly rounded to truncate (
Fig.12
); tergite IX almost completely divided longitudinally, connected only on anterior margin (
Fig. 13
); sternite IX 2.5 times longer than wide; tergite X longer than wide, posterior margin rounded (
Fig. 13
). 
Aedeagus:
Parameres developed and bifurcated (
Figs. 20–23
); median lobe formed by 2 plates, 1 dorsal and 1 ventral, the largest, which extends to the dorsal face, slightly enveloping the dorsal plate (
Fig. 17–18
); internal sac with longitudinal rows of spicules (
Fig. 19
).

Female.
Similar to male, except tergite VIII with posterior margin truncate (
Fig. 14
); sternite VIII with posterior margin rounded (
Fig. 15
); tergite IX and X fused (
Fig. 16
); sternite IX a single plate, extended at base, and anterior margin emarginated medially.

